revision.text:
The '''dangerous proximity doctrine''' is a standard for distinguishing between [[preparation and attempt]] in a [[criminal case]].<ref name=CL>''Criminal Law - Cases and Materials'', 7th ed. 2012, [[Wolters Kluwer Law & Business]]; [[John Kaplan (law professor)|John Kaplan]], [[Robert Weisberg]], [[Guyora Binder]], {{ISBN|978-1-4548-0698-1}}, [https://law.stanford.edu/publications/criminal-law-cases-and-materials-7th-edition/]</ref>{{rp|683}} It was advocated by Justice [[Oliver Wendell Holmes Jr.]]<ref name=CL/>{{rp|683}} The standard is not a clear bright line. The evidence that preparatory acts are an actual attempt is considered to be stronger if the offense is more probable and more grave or serious.<ref name=CL/>{{rp|683}} It has similarities with the [[physical proximity doctrine]].<ref name=CL/>{{rp|683}}

