'''Daniel N. Robinson''' (March 9, 1937 – September 17, 2018)<ref>[http://commentary.jameswilsoninstitute.org/2018/09/remembering-daniel-nicholas-robinson-1937-2018/ Remembering Daniel Nicholas Robinson (1937-2018)]</ref> was an American philosopher who was a [[professor]] of [[philosophy]] at [[Georgetown University]] and a [[fellow]] of the faculty of philosophy at [[Oxford University]].

== Career ==
Robinson has published in a wide variety of subjects, including [[moral philosophy]], the [[philosophy of psychology]], [[legal philosophy]], the [[philosophy of the mind]], [[intellectual history]], [[legal history]], and the [[history of psychology]]. He has held academic positions at [[Amherst College]], [[Georgetown University]], [[Princeton University]], and [[Columbia University]]. In addition, he served as the principal consultant to [[PBS]] and the [[BBC]] for their award-winning series "The Brain" and "The Mind", and he lectured for [[The Great Courses]]' series on Philosophy. He is on the Board of Consulting Scholars of Princeton University's James Madison Program in American Ideals and Institutions<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jmp.princeton.edu/about/people/james-madison-society|title=James Madison Society {{!}} James Madison Program|website=jmp.princeton.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-09-02}}</ref> and is a Senior Fellow of [[BYU]]'s Wheatley Institution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wheatley.byu.edu/the-wheatley-institution-organization/|title=The Wheatley Institution {{!}} Organization|website=wheatley.byu.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-02}}</ref> In 2011 he received the Gittler Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apa.org/apf/funding/gittler.aspx?tab=4|title=APF Joseph B. Gittler Award|last=|first=|date=|website=|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170902050037/https://www.apa.org/apf/funding/gittler.aspx?tab=4|archive-date=2017-09-02|dead-url=yes|access-date=2017-09-02}}</ref> from the [[American Psychological Association]] for significant contributions to the philosophical foundations of Psychology. "

== Primary interests ==
Robinson’s interests range over the brain sciences, philosophy, law and intellectual history. Several of his works are illustrative of these interests. Regarded as a classic in its field, his ''An Intellectual History of Psychology''<ref>{{cite book|last1=Robinson|first1=Daniel N.|title=An intellectual history of psychology|date=1995|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|location=Madison, WI|isbn=978-0-299-14844-7|edition=3rd}}</ref> was praised by [[Ernest Hilgard]] for its “…development of ideas as they provide alternative perspectives on the nature of mind…The reader is carried along on a genuine intellectual adventure."<ref name="University of Wisconsin Press">{{cite web|title=University of Wisconsin Press|url=http://uwpress.wisc.edu/books/0136.htm.|accessdate=July 2014}}</ref>
Robinson’s enduring interest in Aristotle’s thought is summarized in ''Aristotle’s Psychology'',<ref>{{cite book|last1=Robinson|first1=Daniel N.|title=Aristotle's psychology|date=1999|publisher=Joe Christensen Inc.|location=[S.l.]|isbn=978-0-9672066-0-8}}</ref> which Deborah Modrak described as “Easy to read and informative” predicting that it would “no doubt prompt readers to reflect on the relevance of Aristotle’s work to modern psychology…” (International Studies in Philosophy, Volume 23, Issue 3, 1991; pp.&nbsp;142–143). In this connection, Robinson was among the small group assembled by [[Martin Seligman]] in 1999 to develop the framework for Positive Psychology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ppc.sas.upenn.edu/posclinpsychchap.htm|title=Positive Clinical Psychology|date=2014-10-01|access-date=2017-09-02|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141001132438/http://www.ppc.sas.upenn.edu/posclinpsychchap.htm|archivedate=2014-10-01|df=}}</ref>

In ''Wild Beasts and Idle Humours'',<ref>{{cite book|last1=Robinson|first1=Daniel N.|title=Wild beasts & idle humours : the insanity defense from antiquity to the present|date=1998|publisher=Harvard University Press|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|isbn=978-0-674-95290-4|edition=1st Harvard University Press pbk.}}</ref> Robinson offers a treatise on the relationship between science and jurisprudence as this developed from ancient to contemporary times.  Michael Perlin describes the book as “truly unique. It synthesizes material that I do not believe has ever been considered in this context, and links up the historical past with contemporaneous values and politics. Robinson effortlessly weaves religious history, literary history, medical history, and political history, and demonstrates how the insanity defense cannot be fully understood without consideration of all these sources.”   Robert Kinscherff states that it “…reads like the inner workings of a fascinating and disciplined narrative mind.”<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hup.harvard.edu/catalog.php?isbn=9780674952904&content=reviews|title=Wild Beasts and Idle Humours — Daniel N. Robinson {{!}} Harvard University Press|website=www.hup.harvard.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-09-02}}</ref>

Robinson’s major work in moral philosophy is ''Praise and Blame: Moral Realism and Its Application''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Robinson|first1=Daniel N.|title=Praise and blame : moral realism and its application|date=2002|publisher=Princeton University Press|location=Princeton, N.J.|isbn=978-0-691-05724-8}}</ref> Reviewing the book in Review of  Metaphysics, Jude P. Dougherty writes, “The richness of this work cannot be comprehended in one reading.  Whether the reader agrees or not with the author, one has much to learn from the profundity of Robinson's insight into the framing of moral judgment”.  (Rev. Metaphys., 2003, vol. 56, 899-900.)

Central to Robinson’s concerns are the conceptual and philosophical foundations of psychology and related subjects.   Of Robinson’s ''Philosophy of Psychology'',<ref>{{cite book|last1=Robinson|first1=Daniel N.|title=Philosophy of psychology|date=1985|publisher=Columbia University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-231-05923-7}}</ref> William Dray wrote that “this highly readable book squarely addresses fundamental metaphysical, epistemological and methodological problems…His clear and informed treatment…offers salutary challenge to much conventional wisdom on the nature and prospects of psychological science.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=KJBMlurP9P0C&pg=PA177&lpg=PA177&dq=daniel+robinson+philosophy+of+psychology+william+dray#v=onepage&q=daniel%20robinson%20philosophy%20of%20psychology%20william%20dray&f=false|title=Philosophy of Psychology|isbn=978-0-231-05923-7|author1=Robinson|first1=Daniel N|year=1985}}</ref>”

