{{Wiktionary|intrinsic|extrinsic|innate}}
{{for|intrinsic and extrinsic properties in philosophy|Intrinsic and extrinsic properties (philosophy)}}
{{Confuse|intensive and extensive properties}}
An '''intrinsic''' property is a property of a system or of a material itself or within. It is independent of how much of the material is present and is independent of the form of the material, e.g., one large piece or a collection of small particles. Intrinsic properties are dependent mainly on the chemical composition or structure of the material.<ref>Food and Packaging Engineering (IFNHH, Massey University, NZ)</ref>

A property that is not essential or inherent is called an '''extrinsic''' property. For example, [[density]] is an intrinsic property of any [[Physical body|physical object]], whereas '''belonging to something''' is an extrinsic property that depends on another object.

In biology, intrinsic effects originate from inside an organism or cell, such as an [[autoimmunity|autoimmune]] disease or [[intrinsic immunity]].

