{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}} {{korean name|Jeong}} {{Infobox Korean name | title=[[Korean name]] | hangul=정구 | hanja=[[wikt:鄭|鄭]] [[wikt:逑|逑]] | rr=Jung Gu | mr=Jeong Gu | img= | imgwidth=250px | hangulja=도가, 가보 | hanjaja=[[wikt:道|道]] [[wikt:可|可]], [[wikt:可|可]] [[wikt:父|父]] | rrja=Doga, Gabo | mrja=Dogah, Gabo | hangulho=한강, 회연야인 | hanjaho=[[wikt:寒|寒]] [[wikt:岡|岡]], [[wikt:檜|檜]] [[wikt:淵|淵]] [[wikt:野|野]] [[wikt:人|人]] | rrho=Hangang, Hoiyunyain | mrho=Hangang, Hoiyunyain | hangulph=문목 | hanjaph=[[wikt:文|文]] [[wikt:穆|穆]] | rrph=Munmog | mrph=Moonmok }}
'''Jeong Gu''' (1543–1620), also spelled as '''Jung Goo''', was [[Korea]]n philosopher, politician, historian and writer, Confucian scholars of the [[Joseon Dynasty]]s. learn from [[Yi Hwang]]<ref>learned 1563~1573</ref> and [[Cho Shik]].<ref>learned 1566~1573</ref> a key figure of the [[Neo-Confucianism|Neo-Confucia]]n literati, he established the Yeongnam School and set up the [[Baikmaewon]](백매원, 百梅園<ref>[http://100.daum.net/encyclopedia/view.do?docid=b19j0999a Jeong gu]</ref>), a private Confucian academy. his nickname was '''Hangang'''(한강, 寒岡)·Hoiyunyain(회연야인, 檜淵野人), courtesy name was Dogah(도가, 道可), Gabo(가보, 可父).
he was korean Confucian scholars and Ideological successor of [[Yi Hwang]] and [[Cho Shik]], moral support of [[Nanman|South Man]] Party(남인, 南人) and [[North Man]] Party(북인, 北人)s. his master of [[Heo Mok]] and [[Yun Hyu]], [[Yun Seondo]], there's Yesong ontroversy(예송논쟁) then polemic of [[Nanman|South Man]] Party's.
